Concern about security in Mozambique is growing as a result of the conflict of influential people
Under the top-down statue of Samorea Meshel, the founding president of Mozambique, thousands of people gathered in the center of Maputo to chanting slogans of peace at one of the rare demonstrations here.
“We want a return to peace; we want stability,” said Vanessa de Sousa, executive director of the investment company.
Fearing for the future of her country, she changed her business suit to a T-shirt decorated with “We demand security” in Portuguese, and joined the crowd on Thursday in the capital’s Independence Square.
For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government troops and Renamo — one of the most violent clashes since the armor since the armor since the truce was made more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known rebel movement that was supported first by the White Authorities of Rhodesia, and then by the South African government of the apartheid era as part of efforts to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the 1992 truce, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back to a full-scale conflict, but recent events have forced foreign investors and local residents to be nervous.
Rates are high for a fast-growing economy as the discovery of huge offshore gas and coal deposits in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion as investments in the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US.
The ruling Frelimo party, the leading political force since 1975, and Renamo’s party accuse each other of the tensions.
Renamo’s party claims that the government has become the instigator of the last clashes, attacking its members in the province of Sofala, the traditional Renamom stronghold, on October 17.
The attacks on former rebels then escalated as government forces attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakam, the group's leader, Fernando Mazanga, a spokesman for Renamo, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo of initiating clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armandu Gebuza has tried to dispel concerns about instability.
Hebuza told AFP, a French news agency on Wednesday that Mr. Dhlakama felt like a “loser” wanted to use “everything left of his strength to try to prove that he could impose his own decisions on the government.”
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, fears rose after reports that Mazanga declared Renamo’s refusal to renatomate the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he meant non-compliance with the Frelimo party party.
“Our goal is to return to negotiations, but to take a serious scale,” Mazanga said.
Previous negotiations between the parties have done little to ease the tension that has intensified a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Geuba and Dhlakam) facing their foreheads,” said Joseph Hanlon, open-University lecturer and expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them is ready to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo’s party, which is trying to achieve electoral reforms, has already announced that it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted this pressure as an attempt to weaken the move to achieve concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of the votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Momorac Democrat Movement (MDM), which is based on a former member of Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in this election.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Gebuza, who is due to step down next year, when his second term ends, wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to resign as president,” Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capabilities Renamo has, but it has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and cars on a key highway leading from north to south.
Most of the skirmishes took place in Sofala province, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but includes Beira, a port that mining companies, including Rio Tinto and Vale, are using to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of railway tracks about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazang was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
Renamo’s party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique,” Mazana said.
The instability has heightened government discontent, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow pace of development and recent kidnappings, says Fernando Lima, head of an independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the responsibility for the future of the country is borne by the government and the president, who must find a solution to these problems,” he says.
Omar Sultuan, a participant in the demonstration, said that people just want stability.
“No one cares about Renamo or Frelmo, they just want to renew the world, they want free access to roads,” he said.
The rules for the use of electronic devices on aircraft in Australia will remain in force
Passengers of Australian airlines will need to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite measures in the United States to soften the rules regarding these devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has allowed U.S. carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during take-off and landing, provided they remain in Flight Mode.
Passengers can already do this during the main part of the flight, but it is annoyed for many that they do not have access to their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are considering this decision, which demanded that US airlines carry out a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but indicated that they do not plan to change their procedures in the near future.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also noted that they were considering the announcement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases are still in effect in Australia.
“The Civil Aviation Safety Authority currently does not have special rules governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft,” he said.
This issue is governed by the rules that require air carriers to maintain safety at any time, and passengers to comply with the safety rules, which they are reported by crew members.
Virgin, which has already discussed with the Civil Aviation Safety Authority, the expansion of its entertainment system with Wi-Fi on board, was not against the changes, but said it would follow the regulator’s instructions.
“We would welcome the consideration by the Office of Civil Aviation Flight Safety of the issue of allowing the use of electronic devices, because we really think that this will improve the quality of customer service now that it (on-board wireless entertainment system) is on our aircraft,” the spokeswoman said.
Qantas said she would follow the rules currently in force.
“Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and in the near future we do not plan to change it,” she said.
The FAU ruling applies to American airlines.
Nevertheless, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly carefully study the decision of the FAA and the reasons that caused it.
For US carriers, the impact of the ruling will vary from airline to the airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove that their aircraft have resistance to radio interference from mobile devices, as well as to review manuals, training materials, rules for the carriage of hand luggage and instructions for passengers.
“Once the airline has tested and confirms the immunity of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, light electronic devices such as tablets, e-books and smartphones, at any height,” the FAW said.
In rare cases, poor visibility, the crew will give instructions to passengers to turn off their devices during the landing.
In addition, according to the recommendation of the group, the heavier devices shall be located under the seats or in the upper luggage compartments during takeoff and landing.
