Scientists have shed light on how the dog’s tail movements are related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wag their tail in the right direction (from the dog’s point of view), while the alarmed dogs wave their tails predominantly to the left side.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family may notice these subtle differences in the wolf of the tail and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: “It is well known that people have the left and right sides of the brain in different ways involved in the formation of adoure that causes positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at it in other species.
He added that just like humans, dogs control the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to versatile mowinging the tails of other dogs, researchers watched the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the frequency of the animal heartbeat and analyzed their behavior.
It is likely that soon we will know why their tails sometimes head in one direction, and sometimes to the other
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed dogs videos with dogs – either naturalistic versions, or silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that otherwise the unexpecting dog moved the tail to the right (from the point of view of the wagging tail of the dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail leaned mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog’s tail wagging), their heartbeaturururururured and they looked alarmed.
Prof. Vallortigara said he didn’t think dogs had intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that the dogs learned from their experience, what movements they should worry about and what ones should not.
He remarks: “If there are several meetings with other dogs and often wilt their tail to one side is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.”
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of the emotions of their animal.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting researcher at the University of Bristol veterinary school, said it was not the first study to check whether the left and right sides are important for dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left, if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right, if they look at a satisfied dog.
And in another scientific work of Victoria University in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach the robot dog, when the wilting of her tail was headed to the left, not to the right, instead of becoming anxious, the opposite behavior towards the Italian study.”
He said the differences could be because dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to explore how dogs respond to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is plenty of evidence for different mammals that two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon realize why their tails sometimes head in one direction, and sometimes to another.
Is the elite of Europe ready to do business with England?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with an obligation to gather business representatives and determine what changes the creators of wealth and jobs of the UK want to see in relations with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most complete survey of British business leaders, asking them to express their thoughts on the UK, business and the EU.
YouGov has surveyed more than 1000 business leaders representing a wide range of businesses in the UK in size, sectors and regions.
The conclusions of the survey will be a surprise to many.
We have found that the vast majority of businesses are currently looking for export opportunities outside Europe, paying special attention to countries that are modernizing and growing, while EU countries are in stagnation.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than wasting time on a long and difficult process of reforming the confusing EU institutions.
When asked about their views on specific political issues, from antitrust regulation to product laws, most business leaders believed that the control of these key areas of competence should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, and business representatives said that the costs of regulation from Brussels now outweigh the advantages of being in the trading zone of Europe, even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European of all companies, agreed with this.
The latest and most indicative is that our survey of business executives has found that a clear majority wants the UK to pursue a course of a treaty change and on trade-based relations, not a policy.
This result, which was seen among enterprises of all sizes and largest business groups, shows that the business insists on a “significant change” that will return the authority back to the UK.
The rates are high – achieving changes in the contract and more favorable conditions for the UK will ensure a 16 percent vote shift to stay in the EU.
The prime minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of UK membership in the EU.
It also shows that the business expects the revision to lead to a significant shift in the current balance of power back towards the UK.
The best conditions for British businesses are possible and become more and more necessary as the eurozone embarks on the path of a closer economic and financial association.
Priority should be given to jobs and economic growth in the UK, and, as the results of our survey show, for business this means increased focus on trade and fundamental changes in the regulatory activities of Brussels.
