Russia Outside the Fight for Cultutage CAIDSs by Cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities were observed in most megacities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reconfiguration and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for car trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
The example of Singapore is widely known, where a rigid quota of the increase in the number of private cars has been introduced, and the right to purchase them is bought at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have imposed a fee for entering the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, the so-called green zones are introduced, where only cars with a certain eco-class are allowed to enter, which also uses high-quality fuel (including biofuels or electric vehicles).
The Beijing Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a “five-year clean air plan” in 2012 with a total cost of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
As the director of the Department for Transportation Control of the Municipal Bureau of Environmental Protection of Beijing, Lee Kunsheng, told Kommersant, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, an increase in the number of private cars to a level not exceeding 6 million (now 5.2 million), as well as an increase of no more than 5% of fuel use per vehicle.
According to the agency, now vehicles in Beijing are responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, urban measures of the “green five-year plan” include the transition to European standards of fuel, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and labeling of cars and fuel, the restriction on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, the ban on the use of obsolete vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs to replace old cars with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric vehicles (including public transport).
Among the automotive innovations of Beijing also includes a ban for all private cars on movement within the fifth transport ring (there are six of them in the capital of the PRC) one day a week (there is information contained in the vehicle number plate), as well as the issuance of registration plates for lottery-based cars (for example, in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of permits for registration of private cars in Beijing was only a third of the number of 2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011, the “mobile sources” accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In Russia, so far only begin to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy at HSE, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road trips is obviously unpopular, they can be taken by society only if they are utterly universal.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem associated with the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters of poorly sensitive to any regulatory influences - official and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand. (about 5% of the total number of the fleet of Moscow).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study where the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface area and the number of vehicles is analyzed.
The main conclusions of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads by half times required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking, but storage of cars, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (in order that the streets become more friendly for pedestrians), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the protected area of the historical center (a total area of about 3212 hectares, covering a number of central areas of the city).
The rise in price of fuel will lead to a tax maneuver, which provides for an increase in the mineral extraction tax (MET) on oil simultaneously with the reduction of export duties and an increase in excise taxes.
According to experts, these measures can bring an additional 619.3 billion rubles to the budget.
Trip on the mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural areas in Cameroon
Bwellet and his team spend almost every weekend, taking hundreds of patients
In this Western African country, there are not so many doctors – only one in 5000 people
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwellle is one of the top 10 characters in CNN 2013.
You can vote for him or for any of the other 10 main characters to become the Hero of the Year of CNN.
This person will receive $ 250 000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father coming back to life and re-entered unconsciously, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamefa Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma, which reminded herself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” Georges Bwelle said.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwellé accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle said.
- You can leave the house at 5 am, run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Bwellle’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor for 5000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of the health care spending in it are private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwellet was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwellle and his volunteer team performed 700 free surgeries.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at the Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have been assisting almost 32 000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to another 30 people are stuffed in vans, tied medical supplies to rooftops and travel to rough terrain to visit the villages in need of help.
They are not always lucky.
More than once they had to push cars through the rivers and dirt.
But when they come, they are met as real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is really a pretext for a holiday, and Bwellet with his broad smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We accept 500 people on every trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – documents required for school that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school building, municipality or in the house; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative zone to make room for the next person.
Using a generator for lighting operating and sanitary handling equipment, Bwellé and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an unbearable pace, but the dedication of the team usually helps to support village musicians.
“They’ve been hitting the drums all night so we’re awake and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, has conducted 700 free operations over the past year, and they know that their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free operation he received for the treatment of the hernia will allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical techniques at the weekend and work at the hospital, surgeon Bwelle also works at night at private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
This second work, he said, provides 60% of the funding of its non-profit organization; the rest are covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s asleep,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year physician student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in the Bwellle group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses such as O’Malley, coming from the US and Europe to join Bwell in the implementation of his tasks, this is an opportunity for practice they would never have at home.
“We were able to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold the tools for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never have gotten such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their meals, transport and training are paid for by Bwellé.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon indefinitely.
For Bwell, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
To help to live a happy life to others, to fulfill the promise given to his father is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I’m doing this job,” Bwelle said.
- And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to ASCOVIME website and see how you can help.
