Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment for unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of this growth.
Recently, it is completely due to consumption, which almost does not slow down,” said the chief economist of Goldman Sachs for Russia Clemens Grave, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal growth of wages in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will optimize staff costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages are growing by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
Companies have faced a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to redundancy and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business can not raise wages, says the chief economist of Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
To lure employees from the outside or keep the current ones, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia is supported by a very rapid growth of consumer lending.
According to Mr. Graf, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the country's economy.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, the money does not diverge on the economy, but return to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expect an increase in overdue loans.
They are taken mainly by poor people who have nothing to provide for security.
Interest on such loans is high.
As a result, they are often not returned,” said Mr. Graphe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment of unsecured loans.
Director of the HSE Banking Institute Vasily Solodkov already sees signs of a brewing banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, having no access to cheap resources that state banks have, were forced to raise funds of the population at high interest.
In response, state banks went on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - the economist continues.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state-owned banks do not refuse dumping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, Vasily Solodkov believes.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers the harbinger of mass collapse.
“The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was initially not designed for a systemic crisis,” the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without a crisis of non-payment, the investment bank believes, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Partially, the blow to consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if the investment does not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see. the help), the growth of consumption will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is sure.
Vladimir Pantyushin from Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still the fall in the price of oil,” he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to decline at the cost of oil below $ 90 / barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks began to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting,” Clemens Graphe said.
The policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, affects only interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,” Clemens Grafe said.
The money received at auctions of the Central Bank, banks use not for lending to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate immediately changes, this means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work,” Mr. Grafe said and recalled that the state plans to put the ruble in “free swimming” by the end of 2015.
But you will have to either do it earlier, or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he said.
According to him, the ruble exchange rate is now artificially overestimated by 10%.
I will ruscape only one road - to weaken, - the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank drops in financiers at least a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much more.
