FAU: “Air passengers can now use gadgets on airplanes (but not call from a mobile phone)”
Air passengers will be able to use their electronic devices throughout the flight to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music, but not talk over mobile phones, according to the long-awaited new guidelines published Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect the changes to happen immediately.
How quickly such a change is implemented will vary depending on the airline, said FAA administrator Michael Worta at a press conference.
Airlines will have to show FAA how their aircraft meet the new guidelines and that they are updating their training manuals for flight crew members and regulations for styling devices to comply with the new guidelines.
FAW said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in airplanes.
Delta and JetBlue were among the airlines that have already submitted plans.
“Decilitating on the state of the plan, we could approve the expansion of the use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAW said.
Currently, passengers are required to disconnect their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They should not overtake them until the plane reaches a height of 10 000 feet and the captain gives “good”.
Passengers must turn off their devices again when the plane is down for landing and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
In line with the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected from electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during take-off, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most of the new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glaiding, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attenders, welcomed these changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented successfully (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win option,” Glainging said.
We are frankly tired of feeling “joying in school” when it comes to this issue.
But the Internet connection for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages, or downloading data will still be banned at an altitude of less than 10 000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to the aircraft mode.
Thus, there is still no “Words with friends” – an intellectual Internet game in which actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a sensational case: the actor was removed from the American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device at a time when the plane was at the landing.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be put in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly throughout the cabin.
Calls from a mobile phone in flight will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory powers on phone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAW may lift the ban on some electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transport safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are a real problem, not only because they can potentially interfere with navigation devices, but we know from the FCC that they can interfere with cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
The branch advisory committee established by the FAA to study this issue recommended last month that the government allow the wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has been increasing on the FAA to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCasickel, argue that there are no good reasons for security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become widespread.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
FAA began limiting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference for navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began to carry FM radios – high-tech gadgets of the time.
The new airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAA as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Airplanes modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners are adapted for wider use of electronic devices according to new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when pages are turned.
But the signals become more powerful when the devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers, Amazon.com was the company.
In 2011, representatives of the company loaded an entire airliner with their devices for reading the Kindle e-books and flew on it to check for problems, but did not find them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Air Passengers said that he considers interference from the devices real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only individual pilots reporting confirming that devices could interfere with aviation systems, and most of these messages are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAU allow pilots to require passengers to disable the devices during landings on instruments in a limited visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a sensible step towards passengers who now use a variety of technological devices.
“We are delighted to have FAWs admit that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and protection,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Tourism Association.
