New anti-nicot vaccine may deprive the process of smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before the human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystalle of the Waille Cornell College Medical College in New York said the first results were encouraging.
“We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information for the production of antinicotin antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine impact.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, which were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine were “relucidated,” and this is a sign that nicotine reached their brains, the researchers said.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they turned out to be expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine will probably be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they want to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it’s more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They will know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get pleasure from this vaccine because of the nicotine vaccine, and it could help them get rid of this habit,” he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting but warned that more research was needed.
