Frontier Airlines will charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although their ad on Wednesday stated that passengers would be able to keep their entire jars.
The new hand-cook board applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers would pay only by getting to the landing.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said a $100 fee should make passengers take care of payment in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for that,” she said.
Airlines began charging a fee for the first and second bag handed over in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these fees fill as much as they can in the hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why these compartments often do not have enough space.
Fees are one way to get passengers to carry less on board.
O'Malley said that this new collection wasn't really for the sake of making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find a place in the upper luggage compartments.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the exit to the Frontier flight can get the opportunity to carry the bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue can pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said that changing the procedures on the website and at Frontier’s check-in desks are designed to ensure that passengers are aware of the gathering before they get to the landing.
The new Frontier collection for hand luggage will not begin to be charged until the summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street consider the addition of luggage fees a sign that airlines charge enough money to cover the cost of air travel after several years of losses.
However, most of them did not concern the fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first collection for hand luggage three years ago, and another discounter Allegiant Air later followed suit.
The only other airline with this collection is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the added fees.
According to his assessment in a report from December 2011, the fee for hand luggage brings Spirit $ 50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former top manager for Midwest Airlines, was recently flying a Spirit flight, and he was wondering what he would find a landing when passengers faced unusual training Spirit for hand luggage.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my career in airlines,” he said.
I expected to see the grill of teeth and the appearance of a fight at the exit to the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing went fast.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for $2 coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier stated that passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the whole jar and that the coffee share will be provided for free.
She will still give free water.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for a drink in 2008, but abandoned it seven months after passengers began to complain and no other large airline followed suit.
Frontier’s card fee initiative, when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline, is its last measure to attract customers to their website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers, such as Orbitz, from $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contact a travel online agency.
However, Frontier went the farthest in this area.
In September, she began giving half as the bonus miles of a frequent flyer to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut off the premium number of miles of up to 25 percent of the trip.
So, a 1000-mile trip with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a place in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a base of loyal customers in its hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
