Obama campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what might be
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard University School of Medicine.
I read a terribly sad book these days.
I thought this book would inspire me in times of despondency in the second year of the medical faculty and would revive my sense of hope.
It’s called “Audaness to Win,” and it’s a memoir of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing reports on my patients in the evening and going to bed, this book brings me back at a time when politics inspired millions of people and performances could be breathtaking.
The victory in the elections was impressive, and the leading news programs paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates cried out for joy, and my parents took care of all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of strategists was to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
During Obama’s inauguration in 2008, his support was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Return to the present is a rough awakening, like a pulling out of the dream.
It is difficult to remember those days of optimism - they seem to be a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I lowered my first ballot, the changes have indeed occurred.
That was something I couldn't even imagine.
I commend Obama for his great and varied achievements, from passing the law on affordable medical care to the withdrawal of our military from Iraq, the repeal of the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell,” the murder of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the possibility of choosing public health care and the closure of the Guantanamo Bay base among others.
But after countless times when I was on the side of the Obama administration, defending it to my colleagues and peers, I ran out of explanations that I can provide.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Obstructionism of Republicans cannot explain permission to wiretb out foreign leaders or drone strikes against innocent children in other countries.
He cannot explain the collection of data on the private life of Americans by the National Security Agency or the persecution of whistleblowers revealing government misconduct.
He cannot explain the assassination of U.S. citizen Anwar al-Awlaki without trial or non-compliance with state funding and spending limits during presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the findings of the report, which states that the efforts of the White House to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And recently, he can’t justify the fact that it hasn’t been possible to develop a simple website for more than three years after the signing of the law on affordable medical care.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have understood at the age of 18 that management may be contrary to the political campaigns that precede it?
It is clear that working in an elected office is not a predictable program of action, since our public dialogue will be formed by the opposition political party and such random events as the massacre in Newtown.
Nevertheless, all the examples I have listed above shows that they were largely the own choice of the administration.
And that’s what bothers me the most.
I voted again for Obama in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an incomprehensible and rude alternative, it seemed that he was not able to make a decision on his own politics or views.
I believed that in my second term, Obama, freed from the pressure of future elections, would live up to the hopes we have heard about during such a long time.
