Rosbalt agency stripped of media status for obscene swearing
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license to register the Rosbalt agency.
On the deprivation of the agency’s status of the media insisted on Roskomnadzor – for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
During the trial, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, actually denying the publication the right to put forward counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC "Information Agency Rosbalt" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000's, the agency was included in the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the exclusive publications of the agency was (and still make up) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the power structures continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive base of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions, the fact that Natalia Chaplin, the wife of Viktor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project.
At the same time, Chaplina’s role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not fully clear: it is most often called the “head of the project”.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citation or audience.
In October, the agency took 25-th place in the rating of attendance of sites of Russian media according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes about the Kremlin’s helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group “King and jester”, pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media came into force, which prohibited journalists from obscene swearing.
The department found prohibited vocabulary in two videos published on the agency’s website (“Jigit from Krasnodar” and “Pussy Riot desecrated oil flours”).
The other parties describe differently.
Roskomnadzor on the basis of the detected video materials accused Rosbalt of a gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a demand to take away the license from the agency.
In “Rosbalt” stated that the claims of the department are illegal: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, and secondly, the cloth words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed against the claims of Roskomnadzor in the magistrate court - and when on October 22, 2013 the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor, the consideration of these complaints still continued.
However, already on 25 magistrate, the judge made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code of administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if you give up the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone in the course of this confrontation.
The Agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (the statement addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was filed at the initiative of the Communist Party).
The illegality of the closure of the publication was stated by the head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the Chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the presidential Council for human rights Mikhail Fedotov.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that it would not come to the revocation of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be the media in Russia today is a big question.
The gene of speech turned out to be a stimulant for the formation of synapses
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai Medical School have discovered a protein through which the “speech gene” Foxp2 performs its function, stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
It was possible to establish its role in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not correctly pronounce words and sometimes even did not even understand each other.
Scientists have found that the family members had the work of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remained unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least some of their functions, Foxp2 performs as a stimulant for the formation of new synapses in the brain associated with speech formation.
It does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of finding factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, while only on its activity is Foxp2.
The fact that SRPX2 does influence vocalization, scientists have confirmed in the experiment on mice.
When in animals, the activity of the gene was artificially reduced, they shouted less when separated from the mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of sounds produced was also restored.
Previously, the mice also showed a connection with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were injected with a human copy of the gene were squeaked more actively and at a lower frequency than ordinary mice.
Until now, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 controlled by it is connected with purely “mechanical” properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
