And so old that it turned into a fossil: for the first time I heard the “duck” that “independence means passport control”, at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment, lost when retelling an old fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland carry out European orders?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the European crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party “Alternative for Germany” – founded only this year – emerged from nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially displacing the “Free Democrats” (an analogue of our “Liberal Democrats”) from the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan for the creation of a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank and the fetuits imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency led many people to think that the project “Europe” has gone too far.
The euro crisis is little due to the fact that national governments work with excessive budget deficits, this was true only for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – which German politicians want to preserve.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe is at a predetermined position on production capabilities in comparison with Germany.
The only salvage tool is to cut wages and public spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is a deeper problem of Europe’s productive abilities.
As a result of the green energy package implemented by Brussels, a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer, the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas as in the United States.
These are paralysingly unfavorable price conditions, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
No wage freeze in the world will stop the crushing victory of the cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a riot is brewing, especially in France, the ardent self-supporting EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on the same level as Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of obtaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the destroyed French economy in distress.
The result is the right-wing, anti-EU party Marine Le Pen’s National Front party just won the decisive by-elections, dropring the ruling party of socialists to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to British Labourists that it cannot be assumed that the split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What makes Le Pen with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against a single currency.
If – and this is very likely – parties opposed to the EU will receive support in this election, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: soon the growing mood against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something like a vague “Europe (sovereign) nations,” which was liked by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several dependent economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will recover their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the United States.
Nevertheless, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that the UK will be left unheated in the cold of the Atlantic.
In what position does Scotland leave this?
We can choose to become a region (in fact) of Malaya England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, to send Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed in a freer European agreement, provided that we keep its currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in non-Federal Europe.
Otherwise, we should consider repeting Norway’s experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party’s government in Scotland is, oddly the most successful political movement in Europe, directed against austerity measures that received an impressive majority of votes in 2011, by objections to the cost cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Treasury, Alesher Darling, and subsequently formed by the Tory coalition and the Liberal Democrats.
It would now be ridiculous for voting for independence only to take austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
