Early puberty: aging earlier
African-American and Latin American girls tend to reach puberty before their white peers show research.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is close
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame
Experts believe that the epidemic of obesity can be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Eterij is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should mother be frightened if her daughter begins to form breast rudiments and pubic hair grow at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Caplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – it usually doesn’t mean a quick onset of total puberty,” Caplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has only been a slight shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and decreased compared to 12.75 in 1970.
“After breasts begin to develop, it goes away at least two to three years before menarche,” said Caplovitz, also author of “Early puberty in girls: how to cope with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate checking of how puberty will progress.
There is a discussion about what is the actual onset of sexual maturity, but is considered “premature” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in height to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or pause – this is something that a pediatrician can track closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for tests in an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems, such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can ultimately lead to slower growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the level of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Caplovitz is careful with medications, but admits that “suppression of puberty can mitigate the behavioral problems and sensations of girls that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they handle hygiene,” Caplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughters began at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school frightened and frustrated because she was the first among her friends.
There are many advertised theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual media messages are to blame.
In boys - as in girls - puberty occurs earlier.
Caplovitz argues that the premise that has the most weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls from 6 to 9 years old, which links the amount of fat in the body with the timing of puberty.
Other data confirm this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are different explanations.
Worldwide, early puberty seems to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although in boys, hair on the face and pubesis appear at a younger age, the tendency to complete early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors participating in the AAP conference have confirmed the complexity of this topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is found even in infants and children of tooth age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in G. Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to receive instructions from a pediatrician about how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier conversation than expected,” Caplovitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will usually react well.
Girls who bloom early, need confirmation that even when it happens before, this process is a normal part of life.
