Syria has destroyed its chemical weapons manufacturing, the observation team says
Syria has destroyed the main equipment for the production of chemical weapons and ammunition with poison gas, an international observation team said on Thursday, while violent collisions raged in the north of the country, near one of the facilities where toxic substances are believed to be stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian group of activists said that more than 120 000 people have been killed since the beginning of the civil war in the country almost three years ago.
The Organization's statement on the prohibition of chemical weapons was made one day before
The deadline for 1 November, established by this organization based in The Hague, in order for Damascus to destroy or “machify” all means of production of chemical weapons and mechanisms to confuse chemicals with the receipt of poison gas and fill ammunition.
The completion of what is essentially the initial stage of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious schedule that aims to destroy all of Damascus’s chemical weapons by mid-2014.
Destruction of equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Nevertheless, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement was made during fierce fighting on Thursday in the city of Safira, which, according to experts, is a chemical weapons production facility, as well as its storage, according to the British-based Syrian Center for the Protection of Human Rights.
A group of activists who tracked losses through a network of activists in Syria said on Thursday that 120 296 people were killed.
Of these, 61,067 are civilians, including 6365 children.
On the part of the government, the group said, 29,954 people are members of the armed forces of President Bashar al-Assad, 18 678 are pro-government militants and 187 Lebanese militants of Hezbollah.
Also among the dead, as stated in the statement, were 2202 army defectors and about 5375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to the UN assessment of July 25, 100,000 died in the conflict since March 2011.
Since then, this figure has not been updated.
The conflict forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad’s troops have been fighting rebels for several weeks in Safira, many of whom are linked to al-Qaeda groups.
The center said there were casualties on both sides on Thursday, but did not provide specific data.
The fighting underscored the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, driven by their mission to rid a toxic arsenal of Syria, in the midst of an ongoing civil war.
In a statement to the OPCW, which works in close cooperation with the United Nations, said that its team was “is satisfied with the fact that it has tested and saw all the critical means of production and mixing/fuel equipment destroyed by the Syrian.”
She added that “no additional inspection activities are currently planned.”
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 facilities declared by Damascus.
They were unable to visit two places for security reasons, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPCW said that both seats were, according to a statement by Syria, “abandoned and... The chemical weapons program items in them have been moved to other claimed locations that have been checked.”
It was not immediately possible to find out whether the object in Safira was one of the two places that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which is due to be approved next month by the OPCW Executive Committee.
“I welcome the courage and bravery you have all demonstrated in the most complex mission ever undertaken by this organization,” said Ahmet Uzyumciu’s supervisor’s director general in a comment published by the OPCW.
For the third year, the civil war has been facing rebels, mostly Sunni Muslims, with the Assad government and its security forces, which consist of members of his sect of Alawite, the branch of Shiite Islam.
As for other events, the head of the center, Rami Abdurrahman, said there was a strong explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in the coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
