Bombardier’s profit decreases with the drop in deliveries and the number of orders for aircraft
Bombardier Corporation, a Canadian manufacturer of aircraft and trains, reported on Thursday a 15 percent reduction in net profit under the influence of reduced orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and problems with contracts in its railway unit.
The Montreal-based company Bombardier also did not publish any flight tests of its latest CSeries aircraft and did not provide new information on whether ambitious plans for the introduction of the aircraft into commercial operation will be fulfilled by next September.
After the first flight of a prototype of the aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, he flew only three times, which raises questions about whether the stage of testing on the schedule is underway.
The results did not meet forecasts and led to a fall in shares by more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered its estimate on Thursday from “above the average market” to “average market” because of the belief that stock growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in the number of aircraft shipments was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the performance of the transport department’s profit,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if new orders are not announced in the coming months, we assume that the market will become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, where Boeing and Airbus are now dominated.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and for the first time made a flight in September after several months of delay.
However, there are not too many solid orders for CSeries yet – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for flight test results to check the company’s statements about the fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Baudouan was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft would be put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and media that the program was moving forward as planned.
“The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground for longer than expected,” Bodouan said during a telephone conference, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the aircraft’s downtime.
All manufacturers plan to test differently.
We decided to spend the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will happen throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all the others will soon follow it, the company said.
And yet analysts are skeptical of the statement that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
