Two YMCA employees charged with sex crimes before charges against Jonathan Lord, as it became known to the Royal Commission
Two employees of the YMCA NSW were accused of sexual crimes against children before the 2011 charge against a childcare worker in Karingbach Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission for Child Abuse was told.
But in the introductory statement, the commission said that she “never dealt with cases of sexual abuse of children within her organization.”
Chief Executive Officer Philippe Heir was asked about one case when an employee of YMCA was charged with child pornography crimes and another case when the YMCA Caringbah Hall instructor was convicted of sexual crimes against children under his supervision in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gayle Furness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case but did not know about the second.
He acknowledged that YMCA in the opening speech to the commission also made inaccuracy, arguing that “there were external YMCA checks that the YMCA was in the forefront of ensuring the safety of children.”
The evidence presented to the commissiones indicate that YMCA was notified that it had received the second from the end of four possible quality audits conducted by the Department of Education and Communities in August this year.
Mr. Hare, who joined YMCA when he was 21, admitted that he and the lower leadership had missed by hiring Lord, and also failed to provide a clear understanding by the staff of their obligations regarding reporting violations of children's safety policies.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexual crimes against 12 boys during his two years of his work at the YMCA.
He was imprisoned for at least six years.
But Mr. Hare rejected the suggestion that the corporate ethics of the YMCA prevented employees from reporting Lord’s security violations in the safety of children.
The staff testified that they were observing violations, including the fact that the Lord was alone with the children, personally cared for them, put them on his knees, said that he loved one of them and allowed them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Owell, who was under Lord’s leadership and asked her to teach her the protection of children because she was concerned about his behavior, testified to finding Jackie Barnat, a child custody manager at the YMCA department in Karingbach, who was Lord’s leader, “very frightening and often hard-to-reach.”
The Executive Director said he did not accept the staff’s explanation that he was embarrassed to report the situation to their superiors.
Rather, according to him, their friendship with the Lord took them away from the idea of the need to report about him.
Mr. Heir said he presented to the YMCA Board of New South Wales that the lesson for the organization of “the incident with Jonathan Lord” was not “to provide information” on the part of the staff, and the council agreed to him.
Mr. Hare said that the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the arrival of the charges was made by the YMCA Director-General for child custody Liam Wheatley.
He said it was intended to prevent the damage to the evidence, but they “overdue” and the decision was poorly implemented.
YMCA of New South Wales was not a safe organization for children during the work of Jonathan Lord in the period 2009-2011, said the commission expert on child molestation professor Stephen Smolbon from the University of Griffith.
He said there were “serious problems” in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and monitoring staff.
The hearings are postponed until December 20.
